291. ‘ Forthwith the hills of the Phaeacians we bury in mist! ‘ The hills of the Phaeacians’ are the mountains of Corcyra, the modern Corfu, famous of late years for earth— quakes and Turkish nnsgovernnoent, but identified by the ancients with Scheria, the island in which Homer placed the Phaeacians.

aerias: possibly proleptic= ‘so as to become misty.' The adjective lacks support in this meaning, but aer is not unfrequently so used. Generally acrias is taken as: ‘ lofty,’ ‘ reaching to heaven ’ 3 but if the first explanation is possible it agrees better with abscondimus, The latter word is used of those who by leaving a place make it disappear behind them. Homer speaks of the ‘shadowy mountains of the Phaeacians’ land.’
